<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The central issue in this appeal is when a court has jurisdiction to review an adjudicator's decision under the Independent Assessment Process (IAP), the individual compensation scheme created under the Indian Residential Schools Settlement Agreement (IRSSA). The Court of Appeal of Manitoba was correct in overturning the decision of the Queen's Bench Supervising Judge, who set aside the IAP re -review adjudicator's decision and substituted his own conclusion on whether an act was a compensable claim under the IAP. The Supervising Judge erred in law by taking jurisdiction in the absence of very exceptional circumstances, where an adjudicator fails to enforce the provisions of the IAP Model. The Supervising Court's disagreement with the result does not equate to a failure to enforce or apply the IAP Model and does not justify judicial intervention. The standard of review of the Supervising Judge's decision to take jurisdiction is correctness.</P>
<P>2. The IRSSA is a historic settlement agreement that is designed to be a fair, comprehensive and lasting resolution to the legacy of Indian Residential Schools (IRS), and promote healing, education, truth, reconciliation and commemoration. The IRSSA makes two streams of individual monetary payment available to former students&mdash;the Common Experience Payment (CEP) and the IAP. This appeal concerns the latter process.</P>
<P>3. The Appellant JW applied for compensation under the SL1 category of the IAP Model. While in the boys' lineup for showers, a nun grabbed JW's penis over his b athing gown. JW pulled away and said &ldquo;don't.&rdquo; The first-instance adjudicator who heard his evidence found that the incident happened as JW described it. However, after considering all of the factual circumstances and the SL1.4 criteria, she was not prepared to conclude, based only on the part of the body touched, that the act was a sexual assault under the IAP model. Two review adjudicators, acting in succession, found that the first -instance adjudicator had applied the IAP Model and had not made a palpable and overriding error in her consideration of the evidence.</P>
<P>4. Multiple superior and appellate level courts have concluded that the parties to the IRSSA intended that IAP decisions would be final, absent very limited, extraordinary circumstances. Such circumstances should be exceedingly rare, as the IRSSA includes multiple checks, balances and mechanisms to resolve any IAP-related disputes that may arise, such as the one under appeal. These include the adjudicator review and re-review process followed in this case, and possible engagement by the IAP Oversight Committee.</P>
<P>5. Notwithstanding the comprehensive mechanisms in the IRSSA, the Appellants invite this Court to expand the test upon which the courts may intervene in final IAP decisions. Such an expansion would undermine the intentions of the parties to the IRSSA and the objectives of the agreement, namely, the efficient, effective and timely resolution of claims through a culturally sensitive inquisitorial adjudicative process with finality and certainty. Further, any expansion could have a chilling effect on future class action settlements.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>SUMMARY OF THE FACTS</TI>
<P>6. Canada generally agrees with the statement of facts set out by the Appellants in paragraphs 7 to 30 of their factum dated May 2, 2018, and by the Assembly of First Nations in paragraphs 4 to 29 and 31 of their factum dated June 18, 2018, subject to the clarifications and additions be low.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>i.</N><TI><UNDER>The Indian Residential Schools Settlement Agreement</UNDER></TI>
<P>7. The IRSSA is an extraordinary achievement in reconciliation, encompassing residential school operations over more than a century with an estimated 79,000 class members.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 BCSC 839</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Blott</EM></BOLD>] at para 28.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It is a national class proceeding settlement agreement that is a fair, comprehensive and lasting resolution to the legacy of Indian Residential Schools and aims to promote healing, education, truth and reconciliation and commemoration.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, preamble B and C (Appellants' Record [<BOLD>AR</BOLD>], Vol 1, Tab 10, p 113); <CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Attorney General) v Fontaine</SOC><CITE>2017 SCC 47</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Fontaine SCC</EM></BOLD>] at para 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. The IRSSA &ldquo;. . . is a compensation package beyond the jurisdiction of any court to create. It is much more than the settlement of a tort-based class action; it is a Political Agreement.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Attorney General of Canada v JW and Reo Law Corporation et al</SOC><CITE>2017 MBCA 54</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>JW MBCA</EM></BOLD>] at para 60 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 75), quoting from <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine et al v Canada et al</SOC><CITE>2006 YKSC 63</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It provides for and creates unique and comprehensive remedies.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Semple v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2006 MBQB 285</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Semple</EM></BOLD>] at para 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It was negotiated and designed for efficiency, finality and certainty, with a view to protecting vulnerable claimants and ensuring the timely resolution of disputes in light of many claimants' advanced age and poor health.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Duboff Edwards Haight &amp; Schachter</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA 471</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Schachter</EM></BOLD>] at para 58; <EM>Blott</EM> at para 120; <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 813</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Spanish IRS (Stay)</EM></BOLD>] at paras 16-17; and <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 26</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM></BOLD>] at paras 14 and 51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. There are two main compensation processes in the IRSSA. The Common Experience Payment (CEP) is a general compensatory payment payable to all eligible former residents based on years of attendance, without proof of harm and without consideration of whether particular acts occurred.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, Article 5 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, pp 150&ndash;157); <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine et al v Canada (Attorney General) et al</SOC><CITE>2014 MBCA 93</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Fontaine Manitoba CA</EM></BOLD>] at para 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The IAP is an adjudicative process created to resolve &ldquo;continuing claims&rdquo; of serious physical or sexual abuse or other wrongful acts suffered by individual students at an IRS.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, Article 6 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, pp 157&ndash;160) and IRSSA, Schedule &ldquo;D&rdquo; [<BOLD>IAP Model</BOLD>] (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. On December 16, 2006, the IRSSA was concurrently approved by nine superior cou rts in Canada.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Blott</EM> at para 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In Manitoba, the Court of Queen's Bench issued: a Judgment certifying the class action and approving the settlement (the Approval Order);<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Judgment of December 15, 2006 in Manitoba Court of Queen's Bench File Cl 05 -01-43585 [<BOLD><EM>Approval Order</EM></BOLD>] (AR, Vol 1, Tab 8, pp 85&ndash;97).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Reasons;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Semple</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and a subsequent order implementing the settlement and establishing a Court Administration Protocol (the Implementation Order).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Order of March 8, 2007 in Manitoba Court of Queen's Bench File Cl 05 -01-43585 [<BOLD><EM>Implementation Order</EM></BOLD>] (AR, Vol 1, Tab 9, pp 98&ndash;107).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Similar Approval Orders, Reasons and Implementation Orders were issued by the eight other superior courts. Together, the nine superior courts are considered the &ldquo;Supervising Courts.&rdquo;</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>ii.</N><TI><UNDER>JW's IAP Compensation Claim</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>First-Instance Adjudicator's Compensation Decision</EM></TI>
<P>11. JW's claim was heard through the IAP's standard track adjudication process.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Decision in IAP File No W-15603, dated April 7, 2015 [<BOLD><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM></BOLD>] at 1 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, p 1); Review Decision in IAP File No W-15603, dated July 5, 2015 [<BOLD><EM>Review Decision</EM></BOLD>] at 1 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, p 6); Re-Review Decision in IAP File No W-15603, dated November 22, 2015 [<BOLD><EM>Re-Review Decision</EM></BOLD>] at 1 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 3, p 13); IAP Model at p 8 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 21).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> JW alleged that he was sexually assaulted by a nun who grabbed his penis over clothing while he was in the boys' shower lineup, and that her actions constituted an SL1 touching that exceeded recognized parental contact and violated his sexual integrity.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at para 5 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, p 2).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The adjudicator identified her responsibility as being to review the evidence as against the requirements of the IAP Model and decide whether the Claimant established, on a balance of probabilities, that the incident occurred and it was a sexual touching that violated the sexual integrity of the Claimant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at paras 18, 22 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 3, 4).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The adjudicator found that the incident happened as JW described it.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at paras 3, 27 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 2, 5).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> She determined that, although JW had established that a nun had grabbed his penis once or twice over top of his shower apron and that he was embarrassed by it, he had not met the burden of proof to establish a sexual assault as defined under the IAP Model.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at paras 3, 25&ndash;27 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 2, 4-5).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> She found that she could not conclude, based solely on the part of the body touched, that in all of the circumstances the nun's act was a sexual assault as defined by the IAP.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at 3&ndash;5 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 3&ndash;5).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Review Adjudicator's Compensation Decision</EM></TI>
<P>12. At JW's request, a review adjudicator reviewed the first-instance adjudicator's decision under the provisions of the IAP Model. The review adjudicator noted that immediately prior to the incident, some older boys in line were horsing around and touching each other.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at para 4 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, pp 6-7).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> A nun called JW over to her, at which time the incident took place.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at para 4 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, pp 6-7).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The review adjudicator carefully considered the facts and the first-instance adjudicator's findings as applied to the IAP Model. He found that the first-instance adjudicator did not misapply the IAP Model and that her decision contained no palpable and overriding error.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at paras 13&ndash;16 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, pp 9-10).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The review adjudicator set out the criteria required to establish an act of sexual abuse in the IAP Model's SL1.4 category.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at para 16 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, pp 9-10).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Relying on previous decisions under the IAP Model, he found that there must be both an objective analysis of the effect on the victim (violation of sexual integrity) and an objective analysis of the intent of the actor to comment a sexu al assault.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at paras 13&ndash;16 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, pp 9-10).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He determined that through this lens and contextual backdrop, the initial adjudicator did not misapply the IAP Model.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at para 17 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, p 10).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He concluded that the first- instance adjudicator's decision was not outside the range of a reasonable outcome and was not clearly wrong, unreasonable or unsupported by evidence.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at para 21 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, p 11).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Re-Review Adjudicator's Compensation Decision</TI>
<P>13. At JW's request, a re-review was conducted pursuant to the IAP Model. The re-review adjudicator stated that his authority was to determine whether the reviewing adjudicator had correctly applied the IAP Model to the facts as found by the first-instance adjudicator.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Re-Review Decision</EM> at 4&ndash;6 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 3, pp 16&ndash;18).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He carefully reviewed the evidence and findings of the first-instance adjudicator as against the IAP Model. He concluded that the initial adjudicator had properly considered the touching's effect upon the Claimant and had correctly evaluated the nun's sexual motivation in the context of all the facts and as against the criteria in the IAP Model. The re-review adjudicator found that the reviewing adjudicator did not misapply the IAP Model by upholding the first-instance adjudicator's reasoning and decision that the sexual motivation of the perpetrator was an essential consideration in proving an act under the SL1.4 category.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Re-Review Decision</EM> at 4&ndash;6 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 3, pp 16&ndash;18).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He further held that the review adjudicator had appropriately deferred to the first-instance adjudicator's findings of fact, correctly considered whether the first-instance adjudicator had made a palpable and overriding error, and properly cited and applied prior IAP re-review decisions. The re-review adjudicator concluded that the review adjudicator had conducted a thoughtful and thorough review of the initial decision and had properly applied the IAP Model to the facts as found by the first -instance adjudicator.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Re-Review Decision</EM> at 6 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 3, p 18).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iii.</N><TI><UNDER>The Independent Assessment Process</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The Chief Adjudicator</EM></TI>
<P>14. T he Chief Adjudicator is appointed by the IAP Oversight Committee, subject to approval by the Supervising Courts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 16 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 29); Approval Order at para 29 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 8, p 96); Implementation Order at para 8 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 9, p 102).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Chief Adjudicator's duties include: implementing training programs and administrative measures designed to ensure consistency amongst adjudicators' decisions in the interpretation and application of the IAP; providing advice to adjudicators on compliance with the IAP; preparing proposed instructions that better give effect to the IAP for consideration by the Oversight Committee; and carrying out reviews of adjudicators' decisions (as set out below).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 17 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 30).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The IAP Oversight Committee</EM></TI>
<P>15. T he IAP Oversight Committee (the Oversight Committee) is comprised of representatives of former students, plaintiffs' counsel, church entities and government. The Oversight Committee's duties include considering proposed instructions from the Chief Adjudicator on the interpretation and application of the IAP Model; preparing its own such instructions for approval by the IRSSA's National Administration Committee (NAC); forwarding the Chief Adjudicator's proposed instructions for approval by the NAC; monitoring the implementation of the IAP; and making recommendations to the NAC on changes to the IAP as are necessary to ensure its effectiveness over time.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, Article 1.01 (definition of &ldquo;Oversight Committee&rdquo;) at 16 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, p 123); IAP Model at 16 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 29).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>The IAP Model</EM></TI>
<P>16. The IAP's inquisitorial adjudicative model was tailor-made by the parties to the IRSSA. In light of the vulnerability, advanced age and poor health of many claimants, its objective is to ensure an efficient and final adjudication of &ldquo;Continuing Claims.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Semple</EM> at paras 16 and 19; <EM>Schachter</EM> at para 58; <EM>Spanish IRS (Stay)</EM> at para 16-17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The adjudicative process has a cultural component and is private, non-adversarial and designed to minimize further harm to claimants.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 9 and 14 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 22 and 28); <EM>Blott</EM> at paras 29-30; <EM>Schachter</EM> at para 58; <EM>Spanish IRS</EM> (<EM>Stay</EM>) at paras 16-17; <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 14 and 51; <EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> at para 42; <EM>JW MBCA</EM> at para 47 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 71).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. Sexual assaults, physical assaults and other wrongful acts committed against a student by adult employees or other students at an IRS may constitute &ldquo;Continuing Claims&rdquo; and merit the payment of compensation under the IAP.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, Article 1.01 at 11 (definition of &ldquo;Continuing Claims&rdquo;) (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, p 118); IAP Model at 2 (definition of &ldquo;Continuing Claims&rdquo;) (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 15).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These Continuing Claims are particularized in the IAP's &ldquo;Compensation Rules&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 3&ndash;6 (Compensation Rules) (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 16&ndash;19).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and &ldquo;Instructions for Adjudicators.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 31&ndash;38 (Appendix IX: Instructions for Adjudicators) (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 44&ndash;51).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Compensation Rules set out five categories of sexual abuse, ranging in severity from &ldquo;SL1&rdquo; to &ldquo;SL5&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 3 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 16).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. The Compensation Rules also set out a system of Compensation Points assigned to different levels of &ldquo;Acts Proven&rdquo;, &ldquo;Consequential Harm&rdquo;, &ldquo;Aggravating Factors&rdquo; and &ldquo;Consequential Loss of Opportunity.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 3&ndash;6 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 16&ndash;19).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These Compensation Points generate compensation levels that are consistent with or more generous than court awards.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 3&ndash;6 and 38 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 16&ndash;19 and 51).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. The SL1.4 category represents the entry level severity of sexual assaults under the IAP's compensatory structure. In this appeal, the fourth act described in the SL1 category (SL1.4)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 3 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 16).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> applies:
