<BLOCK4><TI><EM>IAP Hearings</EM></TI>
<P>20. Most IAP claims proceed within the IAP's standard track or complex issues track, utilizing the IAP's inquisitorial adjudication model. These adjudications are carried out by specially trained and experienced adjudicators.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 14-15, 17 and 24 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 27-28, 30 and 37); <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 1, 51, 53 and 63; <CASEREF><SOC>NN v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 105</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>NN</EM></BOLD>] <EM>at para</EM> 10; <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 ONCA 421</CITE><PARANUM>3</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> A hearing takes place in a relaxed and comfortable setting in a location of the claimant's choice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 13 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 26).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Reasonable costs are provided so that the claimant can bring a support person to the hearing. Counselling services are readily available and cultural ceremonies are incorporated into the hearing at the claimant's request.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 9 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 22).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. Adjudicators are responsible for managing the hearing and questioning all witnesses. Their role is inquisitorial&mdash;not investigative or adversarial. The claimant is not subject to questioning by anyone aside from the adjudicator.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 9-10 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 22-23).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. IAP adjudicators are tasked to hear and evaluate evidence and are empowered to make binding findings of credibility, determine whether a compensable claim has been proven and award compensation within the IAP standards.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 7 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 20).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They must assess the credibility of each allegation and, for allegations that are proven on the civil standard, determine whether the proven acts constitute a Continuing Claim under the IAP.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 31 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 44).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>IAP Compensation Decisions</EM></TI>
<P>23. Following the hearing, adjudicators are required to produce a decision in a standard format within 30 to 45 days. The IAP Model requires that the decision contain the adjudicator's rationale for finding or not finding compensability within the IAP, and for any compensation that is assessed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 13 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 26).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>IAP Review &amp; Re-Review Process</EM></TI>
<P>24. IAP Claimants have review and re-review rights under the IAP. While Canada has some review rights under the IAP, it cannot avail itself of all of the IAP review provisions that are available to IAP claimants.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 14 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 27).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. If an IAP claimant is dissatisfied with an adjudicator's decision, the IAP provides that the claimant may ask for review by another adjudicator. If the claimant is dissatisfied with the review decision, he or she may ask for a further review, referred to as a re-review. The review and re-review are governed by Section III of the IAP:
<QUOTE><P>(i) For cases within the standard or complex track, any party may ask the Chief Adjudicator or designate to determine whether an adjudicator's, or reviewing adjudicator's, decision properly applied the IAP Model to the facts as found by the adjudicator, and if not, to correct the decision, and the Chief Adjudicator or designate may do so.</P>
<P>(ii) In both the standard and the complex issues tracks, Claimants may require that a second adjudicator review a decision to determine whether it contains a palpable and overriding error.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>(iv) If a palpable and overriding error is found, the reviewing adjudicator may substitute their own decision or order a new hearing.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 14 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 27); <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 21-22.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>26. The IRSSA and IAP Model provide no further rights of review or appeal respecting adjudicators' decisions under the IAP.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iv.</N><TI><UNDER>Directions from the Supervising Courts</UNDER></TI>
<P>27. The Supervising Courts supervise the implementation of the IRSSA, including the IAP, and may issue such orders as are necessary to implement and enforce the IRSSA and the Approval and Implementation Orders.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Approval Order at para 13 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 8, p 93); Implementation Order at para 23 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 9, p 104).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> After fully exhausting the dispute resolution mechanisms contemplated in the IRSSA, certain groups or individuals may apply to the Supervising Courts for directions in respect of the implementation, administration or amendment of the IRSSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Approval Order at paras 13, 31 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 8, pp 93, 96).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Applications are to be brought in accordance with the Court Administration Protocol, which provides that all matters that require orders or directions must be brought by filing a Request for Direction. The regime and processes are to ensure the efficient and expeditious administration of the IRSSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Implementation Order at para 20 and Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; (Court Administration Protocol) (AR, Vol 1, Tab 9, pp 104&ndash;106).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. The IRSSA explicitly contemplates the circumstances in which supervisory guidance may be sought from the Supervising Courts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, Articles 4.11(9), 4.11(12)(j), 4.11(12)(1), 4.11(12)(q), 4.11(13), 5.09(1), 5.09(2), 5.09(3), 6.03(3), 7.01(2), 7.01(3) and 12.01(5) at 36, 38-39, 49-50, 53-54 and 64 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, pp 143, 145-146, 156-157, 160-161 and 171).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> For example, where an application for a CEP is denied in whole or in part, the applicant may appeal the decision to the NAC<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The National Administration Committee is comprised of representative counsel for each party to the IRSSA. See: IRSSA, Article 4.09(4), 4.10(1), 4.11(1), 4.11(12)(a) and (o) at 34-35 and 37&ndash;39 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, pp 141-142 and 144&ndash;146).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and may thereafter apply to a Supervising Court for a determination of the issue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, Article 5.09(1) and (2) at 49 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, p 156).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Similarly, the parties may refer IAP Continuing Claims to the Courts where the claimants' losses likely exceed the maximum compensation available under the IAP, or the evidence respecting harms is so complex and extensive that recourse to the Courts is the more appropriate procedural approach.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 8 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11 A, p 21). And see, for example, <EM>Fontaine Manitoba CA</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The IRSSA does not, however, provide any right of review or appeal to the Supervising Courts in respect of compensation decisions made by IAP adjudicators.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>v.</N><TI><UNDER>The Courts Below</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>MBQB Supervising Judge's Direction</EM></TI>
<P>29. The Appellants filed a Request for Direction (the RFD) with the Manitoba Court of Queen's Bench, in its capacity as a Supervising Court, seeking to overturn all three adjudicators' compensation decisions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Amended Request for Direction dated May 4, 2016 at paras 2 and 26&ndash;29 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11, pp 2 and 11); <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2016 MBQB 159</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>JW QB</EM></BOLD>] at paras 1&ndash;3 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, p 23).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Appellants argued that the interpretation of the SL1.4 category of sexual abuse adopted by the adjudicators in this and other IAP decisions constituted a failure to properly apply the IAP Model and therefore the IRSSA. They further submitted that the Supervising Court had the power to order that the adjudicators apply a different interpretation in order to properly comply with the IRSSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at paras 18&ndash;20 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, pp 29&ndash;31).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>30. In determining whether or not the Supervising Court had jurisdiction to consider the RFD, the Supervising Judge referenced the Ontario Court of Appeal's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA 471</CITE></CASEREF> [<EM>Schachter</EM>].<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at paras 50&ndash;58.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The threshold set out in <EM>Schachter</EM> is sometimes referred to as the &lsquo;<BOLD><EM>Schachter</EM></BOLD> threshold.&rsquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at para 28 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, pp 34-35).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>31. The Supervising Judge found that he had the jurisdiction to review the re-review adjudicator's decision to determine whether the re-review adjudicator had properly applied the terms of the IRSSA, and specifically the Compensation Rules.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at para 35 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, p 39).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> With respect to the Supervising Court's jurisdiction, the Supervising Judge found that:
<P1>a. the Supervising Court's jurisdiction was limited to &ldquo;ensuring that the Re-Review Adjudicator did not endorse a legal interpretation that is so unreasonable that it amounts to a failure to properly apply the IAP to the facts of a particular case;&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at para 40 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, p 41).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>b. an &ldquo;unreasonable interpretation&rdquo; of the SL1.4 category could amount to a failure to apply the terms of the IRSSA, such that the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold would be met;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at paras 39, 56-58 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, pp 40, 46).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and</P1>
<P1>c. Supervising Courts can disturb the adjudicator's findings of fact where the adjudicator's fact finding process involved a failure to properly apply the terms of the IRSSA and IAP, which was not then corrected on review or re-review.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at para 42 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, p 41).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>32. The Supervising Judge interpreted the SL1.4 category differently than the first -instance adjudicator, concluding that a reasonable and proper interpretation of that category does not require proof of a perpetrator's sexual intent or sexual purpose in order to make out a compensable claim.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at paras 54 and 57 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, pp 45-46).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He then applied his interpretation of the SL1.4 category to the re-review decision, deciding that: the first-instance adjudicator had failed to properly apply and enforce the terms of the IRSSA and the IAP; either the review adjudicator or the re-review adjudicator should have corrected this error; and by failing to correct the error in the first-instance adjudicator's interpretation, the re-review adjudicator failed to properly apply and enforce the terms of the IRSSA and the IAP to JW's claim.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at paras 57-58 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, p 46).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>33. As a remedy, the Supervising Judge issued a declaration that the re -review adjudicator's decision failed to implement the IRSSA due to the adjudicator's improper interpretation of the SL1.4 category and ordered that JW's claim be remitted to a first-level adjudicator for reconsideration in accordance with his reasons.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at paras 59-60 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, p 47).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Manitoba Court of Appeal Decision</EM></TI>
<P>34. Canada appealed the Supervising Court's decision to the Court of Appeal of Manitoba (MBCA).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Amended Notice of Appeal, dated November 22, 2016 (Canada's Record, Vol 1, Tab 1).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On May 30, 2017&mdash;prior to this Court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Attorney General) v Fontaine</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fontaine SCC</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (<EM>Fontaine SCC</EM>)&mdash;the MBCA overturned the Supervising Court's decision, finding that the Supervising Judge had erred in interpreting the scope of his jurisdiction to hear and determine the RFD and had exceeded his jurisdiction by considering whether the first-instance adjudicator had properly interpreted the SL1.4 category.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at para 72 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 79).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. The MBCA found that the Supervising Judge's jurisdiction to hear and determine JW's RFD was a question of law, reviewable on the correctness standard.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 19&ndash;26 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 60&ndash;62).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. The MBCA held that the parameters of the right to access the courts for directions in relation to adjudicators' final IAP decisions are those set in <EM>Schachter</EM>: &ldquo;...in the very limited circumstances where the final decision of the [re-review adjudicator] reflects a failure to comply with the terms of the [IRSSA] or the implementation orders, the aggrieved party may apply to the Administrative Judges for directions.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 36&ndash;38 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 65&ndash;67), citing <EM>Schachter</EM> at para 57.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>37. In deciding what constitutes &ldquo;very exceptional circumstances,&rdquo; the MBCA noted an important distinction between: (a) a failure to consider the terms of the IRSSA or the implementation orders; and (b) the correctness or reasonableness of the adjudicators' interpretation or application of those terms.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 40&ndash;42 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 68-69).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The MBCA found that in the latter case, a Supervising Judge's disagreement with a final adjudicator's decision does not mean that there has been a failure to enforce the IRSSA, and does not permit the Supervising Judge to assume the role of the re-review adjudicator and impose his or her own findings of fact, interpretation of the IAP, or application of the facts to the terms of the IAP.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 42-43 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 69-70).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. The MBCA found that the Supervising Judge erred by re-stating and expanding the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold when he found that Supervising Courts may review IAP adjudicators' final decisions to determine the reasonableness of their interpretation of the terms of the IAP.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JWMBCA</EM> at paras 49&ndash;53 and 72 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 71&ndash;73 and 79).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The MBCA found that this expansion of the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold amounted to an appeal or judicial review of the Adjudicator's Decision<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 52 and 71 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 73 and 79).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> that would result in a significant broadening of claimants' and Canada's ability to access to the Courts for review of IAP decisions beyond the terms of the IRSSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 54-55 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 73-74).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. The MBCA found that the Supervising Judge also erred by adopting a standard of review that is not found in the IRSSA, the IAP or the jurisprudence, and one that is akin to the now&mdash;rejected standard of patent unreasonableness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 56-58 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 74-75).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This standard was described by the Supervising Judge as a consideration of whether the adjudicator's interpretation of the IAP is &ldquo;so unreasonable that it amounts to a failure to properly apply the IAP.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 56 and 71 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 74 and 79); <EM>JW QB</EM> at para 40 (AR Vol 1, Tab 4, pp 40-41).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>40. Finally, the MBCA noted that the IAP Model contemplates that adjudicators may have differing interpretations of the IAP because there is no <EM>stare decisis</EM>; and that any difficulties that may arise from adjudicators' conflicting interpretations of the IAP Model should be resolved through the Oversight Committee, not through RFDs to the Courts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 65-68 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 77-78).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In the result, the MBCA granted the appeal and overturned the Supervising Judge's decision.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;RESPONDENT'S POSITION ON THE QUESTIONS IN ISSUE</TI>
<P>41. The Attorney General of Canada states the issues raised by the Appellants and provides her position on the issues as follows:
<P1>a. What is the standard of review to be applied by the appellate court when reviewing a Supervising Court's decision to take jurisdiction over a final IAP adjudicator's compensation decision? The standard of appellate review on questions of jurisdiction is correctness.</P1>
<P1>b. What is the proper threshold for when a Supervising Court should take jurisdiction over an IAP adjudicator's compensation decision? The proper threshold is the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold, which is the very exceptional circumstance where an IAP adjudicator's compensation decision reflects a failure to enforce the provisions of the IRSSA and the implementation order.</P1>
<P1>c. In this case, did the Supervising Court have jurisdiction to review the final IAP adjudicator's compensation decision? The Supervising Judge did not have jurisdiction because the adjudicators enforced the provisions of the IAP Model. The Court of Appeal was correct to allow the Attorney General's appeal and restore the decision of the re -review adjudicator.</P1>
<P1>d. Is judicial review available for IAP adjudicators' compensation decisions? The administrative law concept of judicial review is not available for IAP compensation decisions because IAP adjudicators do not exercise a delegated statutory function and are not carrying out state action.</P1>
<P1>e. Are the appellants entitled to solicitor-client costs either in the event of success on appeal or in any event of the cause? The appellants are entitled to party-party costs under the tariff in any event of the cause.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>STANDARD OF APPELLATE REVIEW</TI>
<P>42. The applicable standard of review on appeal was articulated by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v Nikolaisen</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Housen v Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Housen</EM></BOLD>].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On questions of fact&mdash;whether adjudicative, social, or legislative&mdash;or of mixed fact and law, the standard of review is palpable and overriding error. However, the palpable and overriding error standard does not apply if a question of law can be extricated from the factual considerations involved. Pure questions of law, and legal issues that can be extricated from questions of mixed fact and law, are subject to review on the correctness standard.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Housen</EM> at paras 8, 10, 36 and 49; <CASEREF><SOC>Sattva Capital Corp. v Creston Moly Corp.</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 53</CITE><PARANUM>50 and 53</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Fontaine Manitoba CA</EM> at paras 38-39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>43. T he standard of review applicable to contractual interpretation is dependent on the nature of the question. Many cases of contractual interpretation involve the application of mixed fact and law. However, extricable questions of law that invoke the correctness standard exist where, for ex ample, an incorrect principle is applied.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fontaine Manitoba CA</EM> at paras 37-39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>44. T he Supervising Judge's decision to take jurisdiction to review the IAP re -review adjudicator's decision is an extricable question of law reviewable on the standard of correctness. The Appellants agree that the issues under review are questions of law subject to the correctness standard.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellants' Factum dated May 2, 2018 [<BOLD>Appellants' Factum</BOLD>] at para 32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Supervising Judge's decision is distinguishable from the question addressed by this Court in <EM>Fontaine SCC</EM>. In <EM>Fontaine SCC</EM>, this Court found that appellate review of the Supervising Judge's interpretation of the IRSSA's document disposition provisions is a question of mixed fact and law in which the factual matrix looms large, and is therefore governed by the palpable and overriding error standard.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> at para 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>45. Although the MBCA did not have the benefit of this Court's analysis in <EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> when it released its decision, the Court of Appeal was correct in reviewing all of the issues before it as pure questions of law, subject to the correctness standard of review.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 24 and 26 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 62).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>46. Whether the decision of the Supervising Judge to take jurisdiction is considered on a correctness standard or as one of palpable and overriding error, his decision is in error as being contrary to the IRS SA and the parties' intention that there be only very limited curial review from a decision of a final IAP adjudicator. The jurisdictional question that the Supervising Judge had to consider was whether he had authority to enter into the inquiry asked of him in the Request for Direction. The proper answer is, no. The Supervising Judge should have declined jurisdiction.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Human Rights Commission) v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 SCC 31</CITE><PAGENUM>at 31</PAGENUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> at 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>THE PROPER THRESHOLD FOR WHEN A COURT SHOULD TAKE JURISDICTION OVER AN IAP ADJUDICATOR'S COMPENSATION DECISION</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>i.</N><TI><UNDER>The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold: Very Exceptional Circumstances</UNDER></TI>
<P>47. In <EM>Schachter</EM>, the Ontario Court of Appeal determined that an adjudicator's decision is only reviewable by a Supervising Judge through a Request for Direction and only in &ldquo;very exceptional circumstances.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at para 53.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In particular, a Request for Direction may only be brought where it is alleged that the adjudicator's decision reflects a failure to enforce the provisions of the IRSSA and the implementation orders.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at paras 53, 57 and 77-78.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>48. This very limited right of curial review, which was determined in the context of a legal fee review, was applied to an IAP compensation claim by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF> [the <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM>].<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Ontario Court of Appeal held that the principles upon which <BOLD><EM>Schachter</EM></BOLD> rests apply with equal force to IAP compensation decisions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at para 51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This and other subsequent court decisions in regard to IAP adjudicator compensation decisions confirm the limits imposed by <EM>Schachter</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>For example, <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 55-56 and 60; and AW at paras 78&ndash;84.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>49. Under the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold, an adjudicator cannot refuse or fail to consider the terms of the IRSSA and the IAP Model, or choose to consider others, as this would constitute a failure to comply with the IRSSA and the IAP Model.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at paras 53, 57</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The adjudicator is, however, entitled to interpret those terms, which is part of their adjudicative role.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at pp 7, 31 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 20, 44).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As both the Supervising Judge and the Court of Appeal found, adjudicators are entitled to give context to and interpret the language of the IAP as part of their role in applying the IAP.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at para 45 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 70); <EM>JW QB</EM> at para 56 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, p 46).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Disagreement with an adjudicator's conclusion does not equate to a failure to enforce or apply the IAP and does not justify judicial intervention.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at para 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold respects the IAP Model, the intentions of the parties to the IRSSA, the importance of the finality of decisions under the IAP, and the relative expertise of adjudicators in deciding IAP claims.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at para 48; <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at para 53.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The IAP adjudication process was intended to be a closed process&mdash;a complete code that limits access to the courts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at para 53; <EM>Schachter</EM> at para 58.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It is an extensive and detailed process, which provides many benefits for the claimants that are not available in the court process, including: closed hearings at a location of their choice; having their costs paid to attend a hearing; the choice to have a support person attend whose expenses are also paid; and trained counsellors at the hearings.</P>
<P>51. Further, there are litigation benefits for claimants, including having an inquisitorial rather than an adversarial hearing where there is only one examination by a trained and neutral adjudicator. The claimant is not subject to direct and cross-examination by lawyers. The alleged perpetrator is excluded while the claimant testifies. There is a reduced standard of proof for causation in standard track claims.</P>
<P>52. The IRSSA does not provide a right to appeal or apply for judicial review of any decision of an adjudicator or review adjudicator's decision under the IAP. This is in contrast to other provisions of the IRSSA, which specifically provide for access to the courts in specific circumstances.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at paras 50&ndash;52 and 77.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These are set out at paragraph 28 of the Statement of Facts. These include where an application for CEP is denied in whole or in part.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IRSSA, Article 5.09(1), (2) at 49-50 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, pp 156-57).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> If the parties intended that there be recourse to the courts from compensation decisions of IAP adjudicators, they would have provided for such review in the IAP.</P>
<P>53. The parties intended that the implementation of the IRSSA be expeditious and not mired in delay and procedural disputes.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at para 54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There are multiple checks and safeguards in the IAP and IRSSA to ensure that claims are dealt with fairly, sensitively and in a timely manner and that the process is administered fairly and in accordance with the terms of the IRSSA and implementation orders.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at para 49.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The review and re-review processes discussed above are key components.</P>
<P>54. Further, the Chief Adjudicator's appointment is approved by the Supervising Cou rts and the parties to the IRSSA, and the Chief Adjudicator is accountable to the Oversight Committee.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at para 49.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Oversight Committee, comprised of representatives of the parties to the IRSSA, is responsible to &ldquo;monitor the implementation of the IAP and make recommendations to the National Administration Committee (NAC) on changes to the IAP as are necessary to ensure its effectiveness over time&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 16 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, 29).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It can propose instructions to adjudicators for review and approval by the NAC.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 16 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, 29).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The NAC can make recommendations to the Chief Adjudicator for changes to processes or application of the IRSSA. This is the process negotiated by the parties to the IRSSA to address identified needs for changes to the application of the IAP terms.</P>
<P>55. The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold has been acknowledged by the parties to the IRSSA, the Supervising Courts and provincial appellate courts as an accurate reflection of the parties' intentions regarding the finality of IAP re-review decisions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See for example <EM>JW QB</EM> at paras 25 and 28 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, pp 15, 16-17); <EM>JW MBCA</EM> at para 36 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 65-66); NN at paras 44, 78 and 81&ndash;84; <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 49&ndash;53; <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine et al v Canada (Attorney General) et al</SOC><CITE>2015 MBQB 158</CITE><PARANUM>23</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 2218</CITE></CASEREF> [<BOLD><EM>Bundled RFDs</EM></BOLD>] at paras 164-165.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>ii.</N><TI><UNDER>The IRSSA parties intended that IAP re-review compensation decisions be final</UNDER></TI>
<P>56. The IAP Model has been described by the multiple supervising and appellate courts as a &ldquo;complete code&rdquo; that limits access to the courts, preserves the finality of the IAP process and respects the expertise of IAP adjudicators.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at para 53; NN at para 78; <CASEREF><SOC>Tourville v Fontaine</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 325</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Bundled RFDs</EM> at paras 173 and 178; <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 471</CITE><PARANUM>52 and 73</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The intention of the parties to the IRSSA have been explained by the British Columbia Supreme Court as follows: &ldquo;To put it plainly, when the IAP Model was negotiated, the parties called &lsquo;Done!&rsquo; at re-review by the Chief Adjudicator or his or her delegate.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Bundled RFDs</EM> at para 178.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>57. Notwithstanding its reconciliatory significance, the IRSSA is at its root a contract, the meaning of which depends on the objective intentions of the parties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> at para 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold respects the intentions of the parties by permitting court intervention only where the adjudicator has failed to consider the terms of the IRSSA. Disagreement with an adjudicator's interpretation of those terms is not enough to warrant the Supervising Courts' intervention. If it were, then all IAP decisions would be reviewable by the Supervising Courts, which is the very thing that the parties intended to avoid and disallowed through the IRSSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at para 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. The intention that IAP re-review decisions be final is borne out by the checks and balances that have been built into the IRSSA, such that the Supervising Courts' intervention should be very rarely required. In particular, IAP claimants, Canada or the Chief Adjudicator may raise concerns regarding inconsistent adjudicator interpretations with the Oversight Committee. Alternatively, the parties may attempt to negotiate a settlement outside the confines of the IAP Model. The IAP Model expressly contemplates both of these possibilities.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at 16-17 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, pp 29-30).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>59. The intention that re-review decisions be final is also supported by the fact that where the parties to the IRSSA contemplated that recourse to the courts would be available, they made express provision for that. There is no such provision in regard to IAP adjudicator decisions.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iii.</N><TI><UNDER>The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold protects the rights and intentions of all IRSSA parties</UNDER></TI>
<P>60. The proper role of the Supervising Court is not to intervene in individual cases, but to provide guidance to the Chief Adjudicator and the parties to the IRSSA as to the implementation of the IRSSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 471</CITE><PARANUM>64-65</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This enables the Supervising Court to issue directions where it concludes that the adjudicator has very seriously deviated from what the IRSSA provides. In this case, where the Supervising Judge substituted his own decision on compensability and remitted the matter to a first&mdash;instance adjudicator, the Supervising Court has misunderstood its proper role and stepped outside of its jurisdiction.</P>
<P>61. T he MBCA properly adopted and applied the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold. The strict limits imposed by the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold&mdash;as explained by the Ontario Court of Appeal in <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM>&mdash;best serve the interests of all parties to the IRSSA. The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold preserves the core objectives of the efficient and timely determination of IAP claims through a culturally sensitive inquisitorial adjudicative process that achieves finality. This ensures that the greatest number of class members can access the IAP's compensatory scheme in the shortest possible time, before IAP claimants pass away. Additionally, the IRSSA and IAP contain multiple internal checks and balances to ensure their fair application.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>IRSSA</EM>, Article 18.04 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 10, p 189).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>62. T he MBCA correctly found that IAP adjudicators are entitled to a high degree of deference.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 36, 38 and 41&ndash;43 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, pp 65&ndash;67 and 68&ndash;70).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> IAP adjudicators have significant expertise in the interpretation and application of the IAP.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 51 and 53; <EM>Bundled RFDs</EM> at paras 17&ndash;20 and 180-181.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice Brown, the supervising judge with the British Columbia Supreme Court, has stated that &ldquo;Despite my years of administering the IRSSA, it would be impossible for me to know better than those who have been immersed in the IAP since the IRSSA and with it, the IAP Model were implemented. This is plainly a setting where a deferential approach is both warranted and essential.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Bundled RFDs</EM> at para 180.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>63. T he MBCA did not modify the IAP's Compensation Rules, contrary to the argument of the Assembly of First Nations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Factum of the Respondent, Assembly of First Nations, dated June 18, 2018 [<BOLD>AFN Factum</BOLD>] at paras 61&ndash;69.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Rather, the MBCA found that the Supervising Judge erred by seizing jurisdiction in the absence of exceptional circumstances and expanding the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 2-3 and 70&ndash;72 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 53 and 78-79).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>64. The Supervising Judge purported to adopt the <EM>Schachter</EM> test, but then misapplied it and failed to show any deference to the IAP adjudicators. He did not stop at a consideration of whether the re -review adjudicator had failed to consider the terms of the IAP, as he should have done. Nor did he consider the adjudicators' expertise with respect to the interpretation of the IAP and its Compensation Rules. Instead, the Supervising Judge proceeded to step into the role of an IAP re -review adjudicator, substituting his own conclusion on compensability for that of the adjudicator. He concluded that Supervising Courts may intervene where an adjudicator has reached &ldquo;... a legal interpretation that is so unreasonable that it amounts to a failure to properly apply the IAP to the facts of a particular case.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW QB</EM> at para 40 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 4, pp 40-41).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Supervising Judge went on to apply this novel standard, including his own interpretation of the Compensation Rules, to this case. In doing so, he erred in principle by substituting his own compensation conclusion, contrary t o the parties' intention that the IAP Model is a complete code. He had no authority to take jurisdiction.</P>
<P>65. When the IRSSA was approved in 2006, many IRS students were elderly and many were passing away. Over 150,000 Aboriginal children attended Indian Residential Schools, approximately 80,000 of whom were still living in 2008. By the end of 2016, over 38,000 IAP claims were filed and over 26,000 hearings were resolved. This was possible only because the IAP provided an efficient, specialized and final adjudication procedure.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 62-63 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 76); see also <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 471</CITE><PARANUM>5</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The IAP is now winding down.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 375</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>66. Increased access to the Supervising Courts, as suggested by the Supervising Judge, could undermine the non-compensatory benefits available to IAP claimants. In addition to the non -compensatory benefits outlined in paragraph 50 above, these also include:
<P1>a. only one examination of the claimant by a trained and neutral adjudicator;</P1>
<P1>b. no cross examination of the claimant by adversarial lawyers;</P1>
<P1>c. the exclusion of the alleged perpetrator from the hearing during the claimant's testimony; and</P1>
<P1>d. a reduced standard of proof for causation in standard track claims.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at para 47 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 70-71).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>67. The importance of very limited recourse to the courts is underscored by the statements of the Ontario Court of Appeal in the <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>Doing justice, however, involves more than going straight to what the judge thinks is the right result. Justice requires that procedural rules and jurisdictional boundaries designed to respect the rights of all parties be respected.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at para 63; cited with approval by Hunter JA in <EM>NN</EM> at para 276 (dissenting in result).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>68. The Court of Appeal for British Columbia expressed a similar sentiment in <CASEREF><SOC>Myers v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>All sympathies favour the appellants. The residential schools system is one of the darkest chapters of our history and its pernicious effects continue to be felt even to this day. However, in my respectful view, much as our sympathies might encourage us to be expansive in our interpretation of the IRSSA to permit the appellants to benefit from the IAP, we must not do so. Baron Rolfe once memorably wrote....:
<QUOTE><P>This is one of those unfortunate cases in which ... it is, no doubt, a hardship upon the plaintiff to be without a remedy, but by that consideration we ought not to be influenced. Hard cases, it has been frequently observed, are apt to introduce bad law.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>This too is one of those unfortunate cases. In my opinion, granting the order sought by the appellants would introduce bad law. I would dismiss the appeal.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Myers v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2015 BCCA 95</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>iv.</N><TI><UNDER>The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold should not be expanded</UNDER></TI>
<P>69. The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold should not be expanded. An expansion that would permit the Supervising Court's sustained and frequent intervention in re-review decisions by IAP Adjudicators will not honour the parties' intentions. Moreover, it may have unintended negative consequences to class members. As noted by the MBCA in the decision below, increasing access to the courts causes significant delay.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at paras 62-63 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 76).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This could affect all claimants' ability to efficiently and finally access IAP benefits by adding a litigation process on top of the IAP's adjudication model.</P>
<P>70. The addition of a litigation process following IAP re-review decisions could also have negative financial and emotional consequences to claimants. The IAP Model is intended to reduce the harm to claimants and ensure that counselling is readily available. The IRSSA does not make these benefits available in the Supervising Courts RFD process, as the parties did not intend for there to be further litigation. Additional litigation steps would also increase legal expenses for all parties.</P>
<P>71. To date, the IRSSA is the largest and most complex class action settlement in Canada.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Bundled RFDs</EM> at para 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It serves as an aspirational precedent for other class litigants. An expansion of the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold may have a chilling effect on the potential for future class action settlements like the IRSSA. A decision that overrides the parties' intentions to bring claims to an end through a creative, tailor made adjudicative process, or that otherwise expands access to the courts when class proceedings have been settled, may well affect the willingness of future class action litigants to enter into such creative and beneficial settlement agreements.</P>
<P>72. From a policy perspective, it is preferable to allow the IAP to operate as the parties intended, with its internal review mechanisms and multiple checks and balances. This will respect the parties' intentions, preserve the objectives of the IRSSA and ensure that the greatest number of class members can access a culturally sensitive, supportive, inquisitorial adjudicative process that results in an efficient final IAP compensation decision in the least amount of time.</P>
<P>73. The MBCA rightly determined that an expansion of the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold, as proposed by the Supervising Judge, would result in access to the courts being available for many IAP decisions, rather than limited or exceptional IAP decisions, which is contrary to the intentions of the parties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at para 54 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 73).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This decision should be upheld on appeal.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>THE SUPERVISING JUDGE ERRED IN TAKING JURISDICTION TO REVIEW A FINAL IAP ADJUDICATOR'S COMPENSATION DECISION</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>i.</N><TI><UNDER>The proper application of the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold in this case</UNDER></TI>
<P>74. The Supervising Courts' role is to ensure that adjudicators apply the IAP Model. It is a role of restraint. The Supervising Court must not step into the role of the adjudicator and reassess the facts, re&mdash;evaluate the merits of the case, or substitute the Court's preferred compensation conclusion for that of the adjudicator who has applied the proper terms of the IAP Model.</P>
<P>75. In this case, the Supervising Judge overstepped his proper role and exceeded his jurisdiction. When he determined that the first-instance adjudicator had applied the IAP Model to reach a conclusion on compensability, his inquiry should have stopped. He did not have jurisdiction under the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold to proceed any further.</P>
<P>76. The SL1.4 category specifies that the claimant must prove, on a balance of probabilities, that the claimant was touched by an adult employee or other adult lawfully on the school premises in a manner which exceeds recognized parental contact and violates the sexual integrity of the student.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>IAP Model</EM> at p 3 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 16).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>77. The first-instance adjudicator considered all of the facts and circumstances of the incident involving JW and the nun, concluding that: the nun grabbed JW's penis over clothing in the presence of other boys in line for showers; the act was personally embarrassing for JW; JW did not see the nun's face or expression; the act was very quick as JW pulled away and pushed her hand away and said &ldquo;don't;&rdquo; and JW never saw the nun touch other boys.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at paras 14&ndash;17, 20, 22 and 25 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 3&ndash;5).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The adjudicator had regard to and applied the IAP Model to these facts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at paras 22&ndash;26 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 4-5).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> She was not prepared to conclude, only based on the party of the body touched, that the act was a sexual assault within the requirements of the IAP model.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at para 25 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 4-5).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>78. The first-instance adjudicator's decision was reviewed by two other adjudicators, in succession, to determine whether the IAP Model had been properly applied and whether a palpable and overriding error had been made.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>IAP Model at p 14 (AR, Vol 2, Tab 11A, p 27); <EM>Review Decision</EM> at paras 9&ndash;12 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, pp 8, 9); <EM>Re-Review Decision</EM> at p 4 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 3, p 16).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They both concluded that the first-instance adjudicator's decision was reasoned, and explained that she had applied the IAP Model to the facts and her decision was not outside the range of a reasonable outcome because not every touching of a boy's penis automatically constitutes sexual abuse.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Review Decision</EM> at para 21 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, p 11); <EM>Re-Review Decision</EM> at p 6 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 3, p 18).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>79. Each of the three adjudicators carefully considered the appropriate terms of the IAP and explained the reasoning behind their decisions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM> at paras 22&ndash;27 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 4-5); <EM>Review Decision</EM> at paras 5&ndash;7 and 9&ndash;21 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 2, pp 7&ndash;11); <EM>Re-Review Decision</EM> at pp 4&ndash;6 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 3, pp 16&ndash;18).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> While an adjudicator's complete disregard for the terms of the IAP could amount to the very exceptional circumstances that warrant judicial intervention pursuant to the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold, that did not occur in this case.</P>
<P>80. The first-instance adjudicator performed the task that she was assigned to do: that is, to apply the IAP Model to the facts as proven by the Claimant. Adjudicators are trained and experienced in the IAP Model and in making decisions in compensation claims. Their decisions are entitled to significant deference.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 51 and 53; <EM>Bundled RFDs</EM> at paras 17&ndash;20 and 180-181.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>81. In their factum, the Assembly of First Nations accept the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold as the governing test for recourse to the courts from an IAP adjudicator's decision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AFN factum at paras 76&ndash;80.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Specifically, the AFN accepts that the parameters in <EM>Schachter</EM> allow the court to intervene only in &ldquo;very exceptional&rdquo; and &ldquo;very limited&rdquo; circumstances where there has been a failure to comply with the terms of the IRSSA or the implementation orders.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AFN factum at paras 77.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They go on to then conflate applying the terms of the IRSSA and IAP Model with interpretation of the agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AFN factum at paras 80&ndash;87.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is an important difference between the two.</P>
<P>82. An adjudicator who applies the terms of the IAP, which is what the adjudicator in this case did, is performing the task assigned to adjudicators. A disagreement with the adjudicator's interpretation or application of the IAP Model does not come within the very limited circumstances that allow for recourse to the Supervising Courts.</P>
<P>83. The adjudicator in this case had regard to and applied the factors in the SL1.4 category in reaching her decision, which was upheld by two review adjudicators as within the range of a reasonable outcome. The adjudicator carefully considered the facts and applied them against the SL1. 4 factors. In light of all the circumstances, she was not prepared to conclude, only based on the part of the body touched, that the act was a sexual assault.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Adjudicator's Decision</EM>, paras 24&ndash;27 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 1, pp 4-5).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The adjudicator clearly applied the terms of the IAP Model and did so in a reasoned manner. Disagreement with the outcome does not lead to a basis for saying the adjudicator did not apply the IAP model. Recourse to the Supervising Courts is not available in this circumstance.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>JUDICIAL REVIEW IS RESERVED FOR THE REVIEW OF STATE ACTIONS</TI>
<P>84. The administrative law concept of judicial review is not available for IAP decisions because adjudicators do not exercise a delegated statutory function and are not carrying out state action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at para 51; <EM>Spanish IRS (Appeal)</EM> at paras 49&ndash;51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Rather, IAP adjudicators exercise a function conferred on them by the parties to the IRSSA, as approved by the Supervising Courts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Schachter</EM> at para 52.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>85. As stated by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Highwood Congregation of Jehovah's Witnesses (Judicial Committee) v Wall</SOC></CASEREF> [<EM>Highwood</EM>], the purpose of judicial review is to ensure the legality of state decision making. It is a public law concept that allows, <EM>inter alia</EM>, s. 96 courts to supervise lower tribunals to ensure that they respect the rule of law. Judicial review is only available where there is an exercise of state authority and where that exercise is of a sufficiently public nature.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Highwood Congregation of Jehovah's Witnesses (Judicial Committee) v Wall</SOC><CITE>2018 SCC 26</CITE><PARANUM>13-14</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>86. While decided in a different context, the principles stated in <EM>Highwood</EM> apply with equal force here to refute the Appellants' arguments that judicial review is available from IAP decisions and that the principles of administrative law apply.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellants' Factum at paras 46&ndash;53.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> IAP adjudicators do not exercise state authority. The Supervising Courts' administrative and supervisory jurisdiction over the implementation of the IRSSA<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> at para 31.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> does not elevate IAP adjudicators to actors of the state. The IRSSA was negotiated and agreed to by the parties after lengthy and complex negotiations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Semple</EM> at para 32; <CASEREF><SOC>Baxter v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><YEAR>2006</YEAR><CITE>83 OR (3d) 481</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> at para 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It was not imposed on the parties by the legislative or executive branches of government, through legislation or otherwise. While the IRSSA was approved by the courts, it was not created by the courts. It encompasses &ldquo;. . . a compensation package beyond the jurisdiction of any court to create.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>JW MBCA</EM> at para 60 (AR, Vol 1, Tab 6, p 75), quoting from <CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine et al v Canada et al</SOC><CITE>2006 YKSC 63</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>87. The principles of administrative law do not apply in these circumstances and accordingly, judicial review does not lie. The courts do not have the power to make an agreement for the parties, nor do they have the power to change or expand upon what the parties themselves agreed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2487</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> IAP adjudicators do not exercise state action, but rather exercise a function conferred on them by the parties to the IRSSA and approved by the judiciary. With the approval of the IRSSA came a change in the role of the Courts. The Courts' role changed from one of adjudicating the class actions to that of supervising and administering the Settlement that the parties had negotiated. The Courts also have a role in enforcing the provisions of the IRSSA in accordance with what the parties themselves had agreed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fontaine v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2487</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI>CONCLUSION</TI>
<P>88. The <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold fulfills the intentions of the parties to the IRSSA. The IAP Model is intended to be a complete and final code for the adjudication of IAP compensation claims, with built in checks and balances&mdash;including the adjudicator review process and the Oversight Committee&mdash;to ensure its fair and consistent application. The parties to the IRSSA intended that adjudicators' re -review compensation decisions would be final, absent very exceptional circumstances. Only in such limited exceptional circumstances, where a final re-review decision fails to consider the terms of the IRSSA, can it be said that the parties intended for there to be a limited curial review.</P>
<P>89. An expansion of the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold would not honour the parties' intentions or the objectives of the IRSSA. An expansion would result in the addition of litigation following a final IAP adjudication decision, in which the IAP's harm reduction measures will be unavailable. It will add to the parties' financial and emotional costs with no real benefit. It is not the agreement for which the parties bargained.</P>
<P>90. Affirming the existing <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold respects the parties' intentions and ensures th at the greatest number of class members can access final IAP compensation decisions&mdash;with all of the accompanying benefits of that system&mdash;in the least amount of time. This is of critical importance given that many claimants are elderly and in poor health. In those rare circumstances where the IAP Model creates a perceived unfairness, the parties are free to negotiate individual settlements or to raise the issue with the Oversight Committee. Neither of these options will impede the important IRSSA objectives of finality and efficiency. On balance, the interests of the parties to the IRSSA are best served by maintaining the existing <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold. This case does not meet the <EM>Schachter</EM> threshold and the appeal should therefore be dismissed.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;SUBMISSIONS AS TO COSTS</TI>
<P>91. The Attorney General of Canada does not seek her costs of this appeal.</P>
<P>92. The Attorney General of Canada says that party-party costs should be awarded to the Appellants in any event of the cause, in this Court and the courts below. However, the Attorney General of Canada opposes the Appellants' request for costs on a solicitor and own client basis.</P>
<P>93. An award of solicitor and own client costs, or full indemnity costs, is an extraordinary remedy that should only be utilized in the most exceptional circumstances. To merit an award of full indemnity costs, it is not enough that a claim bear on matters of public importance. As this Court stated in <CASEREF><SOC>Carter v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC></CASEREF>, in the context of a constitutional challenge brought by individuals and a public interest litigant, &ldquo;[a]lmost all constitutional litigation concerns &lsquo;matters of public importance,&rsquo;&rdquo; yet only the most exceptional of constitutional challenges will merit such an award. In addition, the issues at stake must transcend the individual interests of the successful party and be shown to have a widespread and significant societal impact.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Carter v Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2015 SCC 5</CITE><PARANUM>137 and 140</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>94. To the extent that the Appellants rely on their personal interest in bringing this appeal as the basis for an award of solicitor and own client costs, they have not established reason to deviate from the normal rule as to party-party costs. In so far as they rely on having raised important matters relating to the implementation of the IRSSA, the issues in this appeal do not rise to the level of a truly exceptional nature so as to merit an award of full indemnity costs. In <EM>Fontaine SCC</EM>, dealing with whether the IRSSA allowed for destruction of records generated by the IAP, the successful litigant (Independent Counsel) was awarded costs on a party-party basis.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>
<EM>Fontaine SCC</EM> at para 64.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;NATURE OF THE ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>95. The Attorney General of Canada asks that this appeal be dismissed.</P>
